M"><div><h3>What is a time card calculator?</h3></div><div class=3D"style_a=
nswer__AnwuZ __className_cbfc0f"><div><p>A work hours calculator is a simpl=
e tool to work out how many hours someone worked over a period of time. Thi=
s includes break time or time off during the period.</p><p>The time clock c=
alculator takes the total time between the starting and ending time and the=
n deducts times when the employee is not working, such as a lunch break or =
driver rest time. The<!-- --> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time=
sheet" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"nofollow noreferrer">timesheet</a> <!-- -->=
calculator can work out hours and minutes worked to produce the total hours=
 worked between the starting and ending times.</p></div></div></div><div cl=
ass=3D"style_container__N3oOM style_expanded__yg5kM"><div><h3>How to calcul=
ate hours worked?</h3></div><div class=3D"style_answer__AnwuZ __className_c=
bfc0f"><div><p>Without using time tracking software, you can calculate work=
 hours simply. All you need is the total hours in the period and the hours =
and minutes spent not working. Simply subtract the non-working times from t=
he total hours to get the work hours.</p><p>All the information you need is=
 usually on employee timesheets or time cards. These include the employee=
=E2=80=99s pay rate, overtime rate, and information from the time clock. Th=
is is all you need to work out the total hours worked and even the amount t=
o send through to payroll.</p></div></div></div><div class=3D"style_contain=
er__N3oOM style_expanded__yg5kM"><div><h3>How to calculate hours worked per=
 week?</h3></div><div class=3D"style_answer__AnwuZ __className_cbfc0f"><div=
><p>There are two ways to calculate the total hours worked in a week. Here =
they are:</p><ol><li>Add up the total hours worked per day and then total t=
hese figures for the work period.</li><li>Add up the total hours in the wor=
k period (there are 168 in a week) and then deduct time off to see the tota=
l time worked.</li></ol><p>The first method is really common, and useful fo=
r employees who work at the same business location every day. A factory, fo=
r example, will track the time data for its people this way.</p><p>The seco=
nd method is more valuable for employees who work varied schedules or at di=
fferent locations. Over the Road drivers, for example, have very flexible s=
chedules but must also track their time carefully.</p></div></div></div><di=
v class=3D"style_container__N3oOM style_expanded__yg5kM"><div><h3>Why do I =
need to calculate hours worked?</h3></div><div class=3D"style_answer__AnwuZ=
 __className_cbfc0f"><div><p>The obvious reason is so you get paid correctl=
y. Tracking your hours with a time clock or time card will help you submit =
correct data for the payroll or contract.</p><p>There are a few other reaso=
ns, though. Here are some other ways to use an hours calculator:</p><ul><li=
>Keep track of time spent on fixed rate projects. This data will help you k=
now if you are charging the correct amount for your work.</li><li>Track you=
r time spent working over a longer period of time to work out your hourly r=
ate. You can use this for tax reporting and job hunting.</li></ul></div></d=
iv></div><div class=3D"style_container__N3oOM style_expanded__yg5kM"><div><=
h3>How should I use the time card calculator?</h3></div><div class=3D"style=
_answer__AnwuZ __className_cbfc0f"><div><p>You can use the time card calcul=
ator in several different ways. The first and most important way is to work=
 out the number of hours you have worked. By doing this you will save a lot=
 of time, and remove the potential for errors. It means you won=E2=80=99t b=
e underpaid, and you can avoid the possibility of entering too many hours a=
nd getting into trouble at work.</p><p>The second way is to check your own =
calculations. While this won=E2=80=99t save time like the first way will, i=
t will make sure there are no errors in your calculations. We guarantee err=
or-free calculations as long as you enter the correct values into the corre=
ct boxes.</p></div></div></div><div class=3D"style_container__N3oOM style_e=
xpanded__yg5kM"><div><h3>Is the time card calculator free to use?</h3></div=
